The Ukrainian parliament today refused the request to abolish, in the context of a amendment to the Penal Code, those paragraphs on the basis of which opposition leader Yulia Timoshenko had been convicted.
The new regulation, which could have paved the way for the release of the imprisoned ex-premier, was rejected by MEPs at the second reading of the request for mitigation of penalties for economic offences.
Timoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison in October for concluding an allegedly detrimental contract with Russia on the purchase of natural gas.
The verdict is not yet final, in December the appeal of the convicted will be heard in court.
Timoshenko himself describes the verdict as a political revenge of the regime and also in the West the trial raised suspicions of the bias of the court.
The request to remove Paragraph 365, on the basis of which the ex-premier was convicted, from the Criminal Code, was supported by 147 MPs.
226 votes would have been required for its adoption.
