France and the rest of Europe are the focus of investors.
On Tuesday, a statistical storm blew through Europe.
The individual states published their data on their GDP for the third quarter.
The Czech economy stagnated compared to the previous quarter, while Germany and France grew.
Today, however, the bond market is breaking all records.
Investors not only keep an eye on Greece, but also on Spain, France, Austria and other countries.
The statistical offices of the European Zone, Germany, the Czech Republic and several other European countries published their preliminary forecasts on economic development in the third quarter.
Germany’s GDP was expected to grow by 0.5% and France’s by 0.4%.
At the same time, both countries corrected their data for the second quarter, in which Germany recorded higher growth than had originally been expected (growth by 0.3% instead of predicted 0.1%), while France admitted a slight decline of 0.1% (original data spoke only of stagnation).
The Czech economy grew by 1.5 percent in the third quarter of this year compared to the previous year.
Compared to the previous quarter, however, gross domestic product stagnated and according to the Statistical Office, the trend of slowing economic performance was thus confirmed.
The results are thus worse than the forecasts of analysts.
The most important events:
The Czech economy grew by 1.5 percent in the third quarter of this year compared to the previous year, but stagnated compared to the previous quarter.
According to preliminary and seasonally calculated data, the German economy grew by 0.5 percent in the third quarter.
In the eurozone as a whole and in the EU, the economy recorded growth of 0.2 percent between July and September compared to the previous quarter, which is in line with analysts’ expectations.
The Greek economy declined by 5.2 percent compared to the previous year.
