The menu of a fat-addicted child: It does not eat breakfast and sausages for dinner
More than one-third of children aged 9 to 13 have problems with obesity, with 9 percent of all students and 5 percent of all children being overweight.
Recent surveys have shown that obese children are mostly from families with unhealthy lifestyles.
Once again, it shows how important for a person’s healthy development is the environment in which he grows up and the examples that surround him.
On the tables of obese children, sausages are up to half more often on the table than in families where normal-weight children live.
More than 19 percent of the overweight children had French fries for dinner on the day before the education campaign under the motto "Obesity is no coincidence".
In families with thickets, sport is not exactly one of the favorite activities, but as far as the majority of today’s students are concerned, only 15 percent replied that their parents find time for active exercise at least once a week.
Survey of 900 children
The survey took place at the end of the school year last year, during which almost 900 children from primary schools throughout the Czech Republic were interviewed.
This was already the second year of the action "Adiposity is not a coincidence", which is supported by the General Health Insurance and the company Unilever.
So far, more than 12 thousand students from 4th and 8th grades participated in the project.
Unhealthy food and lack of exercise in the family are crucial factors that are responsible for the alarmingly increasing number of children with obesity or even obesity.
“Only half of the children surveyed, for example, reported eating breakfast-second breakfast-lunch-vesper dinner bread five times a day – one of the main prerequisites for a healthy diet,” according to one of the survey results.
No breakfast and sausage for dinner
Experts point out that relative small things, such as the regular breakfast time of the family, are also important for the healthy development of a child.
In the Czech Republic, only 23 percent of the students’ families have breakfast.
And - in most families, everyone eats breakfast on their own.
Worst of all was the finding that one in ten families does not have breakfast at all.
Breakfast is considered the cornerstone of a healthy daily diet.
The survey test revealed, among other things, that people in the families of overweight children consume much more often unhealthy fries.
And almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweet lemonades every day (70 percent)
Although more than 40 percent of the children surveyed exercise, only less than half of their parents do – only 15 percent.
Create your own menu
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to put together their own dietary options according to appetite and opinion.
"What Czech children between 12 and 15 prefer in terms of diet is far from the ideal of a healthy diet.
Among their favorite dishes were many flour dishes, meat dishes and, of course, sweets.
"Alarming is above all the great popularity of sweet lemonades," the final report to this survey emphasizes.
At lunch, i.e. the main course, pasta won just before poultry.
The children almost did not like legumes and the popularity of fish and vegetable dishes as lunch was also very low.
Return to Health
At the same time, the survey also showed that the children are quite willing to change their eating habits if they get proper information.
"In the control group of survey participants who completed the questionnaire after completing the enlightening lecture 'Obesity is not a coincidence', in many cases there was a significant shift in preferences towards principles of healthy nutrition," the results of the project are quoted.
This was evident, for example, in the sweet limos, where many children began to give priority to ordinary water.
In the questionnaire, the children also crossed poultry or fish much more often as the main course of the day and were ready to eat less dumplings or sweet foods.
