V Need for Speed: "The Run" - the illegal race across America
Review
The original carefree journey becomes a routine journey to the early shift through a series of completely avoidable, dilettant mistakes.
Although it succeeded in fulfilling the ambitions for the most part, what good is that even if obviously no one wanted to do a little more.
Even before he got on the counters, the new part with the subtitle "The Run" aroused high expectations.
He promised to move the already aged game series "Need for Speed" to a new dimension again and in the playable demonstration examples he did not seem to be just one of many action racing games.
We were also curious about how the fitted passages turn out, in which the main protagonist gets out of the car and continues on foot.
But as one is already used to at NFS, much is in the end different than one expected.
Sure - they are potentially quite decent arcade races, but overall, the game is narrowed down by some superfluous bugs that have been present in this series for more or less a few years.
So they are actually no longer mistakes, but rather signs of a basically incomprehensible laziness of the game developers.
The adventure starts very well.
For the first time, one is introduced to the story, whose main character Jack has certain personal problems; the only solution seems to be to participate in an illegal race across America.
In San Francisco, on the west coast, you sit on the steering wheel - with the task of being the first in New York.
The basic idea includes a number of interesting elements.
The entire route is divided into ten stages and more than fifty individual races.
This means that each race is held on a different track and that the individual stages take place in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
You don’t have the impression that the game would offer the same thing again and again.
Some environments are quite nice to look at, although the technical level of the graphics does not go beyond that of the earlier parts of the series.
So nothing world-moving.
But driving through the desert, through autumnal landscapes or high up through deep snowy landscapes is visually very pleasant.
Occasionally, untypical elements bring a little variety to the individual races.
In the desert, for example, one is surprised by a desert storm, which severely restricts the view.
In the mountains, you have to be careful not to be spilled by an avalanche.
By the way, the individual races are installed quite well in succession.
Only a few, but they are enough.
For a while you try to overtake the prescribed number of opponents (in principle a classic race), then you have time to catch up (classic race against the stopwatch), then you expect a personal duel with a single opponent.
And the police are also interfering, who want to mess up the whole thing.
A novelty is passages in which Jack leaves the car.
It is more about certain interactive animations in which Jack flees from anyone and where the player has to help him by pressing the right button at the right time.
So nothing complicated.
However, it is surprising that there are far fewer such passages in the game than you would expect (in concrete terms only three).
Ultimately, this is more of an advantage to the game, because this element has at least no chance of getting bored - it is one of the elements that make the game more varied in the context of the above mentioned.
The driving model steps in the footsteps of the previous parts.
That is to say, from today’s point of view, although it does not rip out trees, on the other hand, one could not say that it would be bad.
If you are looking for realistic simulations, you have to look elsewhere.
But an action-packed race will continue to do well for the local driving model, although you could find better in the competition.
Until then, everything is in the best order.
Real problems only appear after a certain amount of time.
In contrast to the driving model, the collision model is not quite O.K.
It is hard to expect a game of this kind to calculate complicated deformations and collisions, but if you have practically no idea of how the car behaves before any impact on any object, then obviously not everything is okay.
Typical example: when you overtake or pass by oncoming cars, you "strip" the other car only easily in some places, but in other, almost identical situations, you get to sling and turn wild pirouettes.
Or drive the car straight to scrap.
Thanks to the restart system, it doesn't matter anymore, but it's always annoying.
The restarts are solved in this way: if you have total damage or land far off the track, you throw the game back to the last point of the track.
Only - in each race you only have five restarts.
Once you have exhausted them, everything starts from scratch.
So the restarts are more like a tool, in case something fails, but you should rather not rely on it.
Sometimes, however, even the restart does not help, there is nothing more than learning the critical section from the mind.
It is extremely unpleasant that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, you have to go through some curves in a very specific way, otherwise you simply don’t fit through.
Elsewhere, you always encounter "civil" cars in the same configuration, whether you come first or fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is especially annoying in situations when you see the opponent passing by two cars in front of you, but until you get there yourself, the cars are already in such a position that you have to drive around or brake them.
And it doesn’t matter when you get there, because everything is designed so that this situation always comes close to your nose.
The counterparties have other advantages.
Throughout the game there are a few places where you are always overtaken by the same opponent at the same place and again here without regard to the time.
Most insanely, this is at the end of the game on the long bridge, which you pass in the opposite direction.
The opponent obviously has to get out of here on devil.
And if he is in front of you, then of course he takes the view, so that you drive your own car a few times in Klump at first.
Sure - you just want to make the game more exciting and exciting, but this intention is so clear that it quickly forgets the joy of the game.
And that is a pity, because despite a simpler driving model, the game is quite entertaining and sometimes so action-packed that you almost no longer know where your head is.
And in principle, it doesn't matter what "guilty" it is - the concept with fifty unique routes, the arrangement of the races in a way that no boredom can arise, or something completely different...
An unusual idea is also the car change over the course of the races.
Don’t miss out on the petrol stations on the route, because this is where you can change the car, although in most cases the car you just have is enough.
The cars are divided into three categories.
The sports cars are well suited for the urban areas, the strong American sedans for the straight motorways and exotic super sports cars for the technical rides, for example on the serpentines in the mountains.
Hand in hand with the mode of game history, the task mode (challenges) also goes - i.e. the races in the individual locations you know from history.
Here you can not only win medals, but also experience points for your own profile, which is common for the tasks (challenges) and the history.
To get to the higher driver level, different items need to be opened up: from the car to the backgrounds for the profile.
This is also connected to the Autolog online function, which compares, among other things, the own achieved results with those of other players and also provides for other collective functions.
One of the other incomprehensible carvers is a situation in the last race in history.
Here you get by car into a subway tunnel (my way), where you rest in the dark on the rails long (my way).
On the speedometer there are numbers between 150 and 200 km/h (meaningly), but there comes a subway from behind and drives a uncompromising to scrap.
In our editors, we will probably argue for a long time about whether this was a blackout of the game designers or whether the authors think us so stupid.
The technical side is nothing overwhelming but at least the visual overall impression is in most cases quite appealing and here and there even brilliant.
All the more annoying is that at some exciting moments the refresh rate slows down and this is sometimes quite dramatic.
However, this applies in particular to accidents with a larger number of participants, where a continuous FPS is of no use anyway.
The sound playback is as far as O.K. and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to reach as wide a scale as possible to young audiences, a soundtrack was created a l<0xC3><0xA1> "something" - but who buys such a game already because of the music?!
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run? The feelings are rather mixed.
If the game weren’t diminished by the totally unnecessary mistakes mentioned, we could have asserted with the chest tone that The Run is the best piece of NFS in recent years.
This is how the game seems unfinished.
In itself a great pleasure, but you should be prepared to see these mistakes with the power of airport headlights.
