Brand Story:
Innovator IBM enters the second century of its existence
If you were looking for a suitable word that characterizes IBM’s strategy most accurately, then this would probably be the word “longevity”.
For the general public, IBM is synonymous with technological revolution, known as a modern enterprise, although it has been a century since its inception.
The basis for this longevity was already laid by her first boss - the visionary Thomas J. Watson sen.
Already he represented the slogan, countless worldwide problems could easily be solved if people were willing to think a little bit.
His slogan "Think!" thus became a trademark for the future giant's life (and at the same time the title of the company's in-house magazine, which was started by IBM in 1935).
This was also the basis of Watsen’s thoroughly prepared corporate culture.
“For us at IBM, this long-term thinking means a continual movement towards the future.
IBM survived and was successful for a whole century because it remained true to its principles and did not shy away from changing everything else around it.
This allowed us to transform the technologies, business and also society over the course of our first century.
We hope to achieve even more in the next hundred years," said Samuel J. Palmisano, the company's current director for the anniversary.
Well-thought-out system
In the 1930s, Watson was already socially caring for his employees – in a similar way to the entrepreneur Ba<0xC5><0xA5>a in Czechoslovakia: the IBM people had paid leave as one of the first American employees, an insurance policy by the entrepreneur plus elegant uniforms as workwear and a well-thought-out remuneration system for the best newcomers and traders.
Similarly, IBM’s long-term relationships with its customers are ingenious.
The company was ingenious in talent promotion from the beginning - as one of the first companies in the world to lift any discrimination - and was able to choose accordingly.
In line with this anti-discrimination strategy, the current plan that Palmisan will be alternated with a woman next year at the head of IBM is also – by Virginia Rometty.
She has been with IBM for thirty years, so far she has held the position of Head of Sales, Marketing and Strategy.
In recent years, IBM has been making so-called online brainstormings, from which many future strategies and innovations grow.
No wonder - there are enough ideas, because almost half a million people are employed in the company.
An institution with a good reputation
Their unwavering position in the business guarantees the company a strong image, both internally and externally.
“From the beginning, IBM had the concept of an institution rather than a mere technology company,” said Professor of Harvard Business School and author of a book on IBM, Rosabeth Moss Kanter.
“IBM isn’t a technology company, it’s a company that helps solve business problems with technology,” added George Colony of consulting firm Forrester Research.
As the company itself emphasizes, it is a difference to be only present in the market or to directly shape it through this presence.
IBM - in the states of its logo for its familiar "Big Blue" has grown into one of the largest companies in the world in a century.
It is one of the most versatile technology companies ever - IBM develops hardware and software, infrastructure, hosting and consultation services in an incredible product range - from servers to nanotechnology.
Of all American technology companies, IBM holds the most patents, and five of its employees have already been awarded the Nobel Prize.
His best-known inventions include, for example, ATMs, credit cards, financial swap, barcode or even the floppy disk.
With approximately $220 billion in market capitalization, IBM was the second-largest technology company this year (equal to Apple), surpassing Microsoft for the first time since 1996.
Looking ahead
Not all products and innovations met the taste of today's customers - unfortunate were, for example, the attempt with its own OS/2, the online service Prodigy or the computers IBM PC jr.
“Business is based on the forward movement, so you can’t be emotionally tied to the past,” says Samuel J. Palmisano.
That’s why IBM has no problem building its foundations on different platforms – and if they don’t work, leaving them again.
Unlike Microsoft, which basically stands and falls with its Windows operating system.
Promising technologies
IBM’s profits are largely driven by services, software and hardware, each contributing one-fifth.
In 1990, hardware was still the strongest with a more than fifty percent share.
Since 2000, IBM has sold little profit-making assets worth $15 billion, but at the same time, it has invested $58 billion in purchasing future-oriented technologies.
IBM continues in these investments even after 2008, when the current financial crisis swept the world like a storm for the first time.
Here, too, IBM remained true to the legacy of its first boss Thomas J. Watson, who increased his investment in the midst of the great global economic crisis.
So far, it seems that the company IBM survives today’s crisis unharmed.
Since 2008, the value of IBM shares has increased by 120 percent in a rocket-like manner and the company’s net profit has grown continuously.
IBM’s corporate slogan is that everything can be changed – only the values don’t.
This is also why it can be expected that this flexible giant will also cope with the next crisis.
IBM History: From Cheese Cutter to Spaceflights
Founded one hundred years ago in New York, IBM (International Business Machines) initially had a rather complicated name - Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It took over the name IBM only in 1924 - originally it was a brand name for a branch in Canada and South America.
The foundation stone for the later company IBM was the merger of four companies, whose history dates back to the 1980s.
They had technologies such as the famous linchpin clocks for registering the start and end of work.
Charles Ranlett Flint became the architect of this new company, who also chaired the Supervisory Board until 1930.
And it was Flint who hired the head of the rival company Thomas J. Watson to help him manage the company.
This leader even overshadowed IBM’s founders – based on Watson’s ideas to date, the company’s invincible culture and identity.
Watson led the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name suggests, began manufacturing and distributing all sorts of machines for trade – from sausage and cheese cutters to cash registers.
During the first four decades when Watson led the company, he doubled its revenues to $9 million and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that he sat in the executive chair for forty years, only then he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, technicians and computers from IBM helped NASA fly into space - to Mercury and Saturn, and in 1969 also the famous flight of man to the moon.
In 1964, IBM developed the first computer family with the same computer architecture - the IBM System/360 series.
A classic PC, which defined the computer standard of the time, was launched in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand, it bought the consultant part of the company PricewaterhouseCoopers and thus entered fully into the business of consulting services and services with high added value.
The strategy that IBM has been paying off over the past three years is the concept of “Smart Planet”.
It embodies the intention to use technologies wisely in areas that have not yet been planned, e.g. to improve the situation in transport and in the city administration.
In the trade sector, IBM recently introduced the Smarter Commerce platform to help traders lead the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
In 1932, IBM established a branch in Czechoslovakia, the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM <0xC4><0x8C>R also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Central and Eastern European Headquarters is located in Prague and is also home to a top-level team of world-class researchers working on the technology of voice recognition.
