Development of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five approved state travel agencies in the former <0xC4><0x8C>SSR: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
At that time, the travel agencies mainly sold only trips to the socialist Eastern bloc countries, and only select people were allowed to go to the West.
And so Czech tourists travelled to the Baltic Sea (to the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the peninsula of Crimea on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when one was also allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a pro-Western course and therefore travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that it was not even citizens of the Eastern bloc (also the Czechoslovaks) allowed to travel freely within the framework of the socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of the <0xC4><0x8C>SSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
Even then, the travel agencies also offered trips to the West, but then you had to accept huge snakes or also sleep in the sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good friends" in the travel agency.
That was not the case for a long time.
The so-called foreign exchange promise - the condition for an exit to the West - was only given to "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so it would have been impossible to raise the necessary financial resources (western currency) for a trip to the West without the commitment of foreign exchange.
The vast majority of Czechs therefore spent their holidays inland, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and dates - a habit that continues to this day.
The Velvet Revolution of 1989 was followed by a travel revolution of the Czechs.
While a holiday in the GDR or Bulgaria was the measure of all things until 1989, the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their holidays abroad in countries around the world last year.
A huge paradox that is no longer known today is the fact that one could not travel to the currently most popular holiday country of the Czech Republic - Croatia until 1989, because it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
Right from the beginning of the 90s of the last century, the foreign exchange obligation in the neighbouring Western European countries was lifted, which caused a huge wave of short visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and to Germany.
The Czechoslovaks simply could not get enough of their travels to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to be there for at least a few days.
For example, the Czech holidaymakers slept in a tent in the park when they traveled to Paris, because who would have had the money for accommodation in a hotel or in a guesthouse at the time.
A typical feature of Czech travel abroad was a trunk packed with canned food, beer and permanent sausage, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech crown - after decades, our tourists were finally able to freely buy the Western currency.
Our level of living and, as a result, the average salaries increased, which led to another important moment in 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, after 1997, travel agencies began to regularly prepare trips through charter flights, making air travel incredibly cheap compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of negotiating volume discounts.
At the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the US, already had currencyless payments with all the advanced countries of the world, making travelling even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-samten" travel occurred in 2000, when, thanks to the high demand, the first direct charter flight to an exotic country - Thailand.
Since then, every year direct charter planes with Czech passengers fly to far-away sunny countries; this year you fly directly from the Czech Republic to twelve exotic destinations.
The 100 thousand Czechs travel to exotic countries every year!
Another important moment in the epoch that marked our "post-revolutionary" development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the U.S. lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, making our country definitely one of the most advanced countries in the world.
In 2008, for the first time, the Czechs spent more than half of their vacation abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, they spent more than 15 thousand CZK per capita for a single holiday, including the costs at the resort.
