Europe's most beautiful pools
Jump into the blue
by Julia Stanek
Ufo-optic paddling pools, pompous pools in Budapest: If you travel through Europe, you can experience its blue wonder - and after a city tour or a hike, rest your tired legs in bubble baths.
A book shows where wellness in the water is the most beautiful.
When Iris Meder went on a research trip in the past one and a half years, one thing was not to be missed in her luggage: her swimsuit.
Lying backwards on the water, she looked up in artfully designed domes, swam towards marble putts waiting for her at the edge of the pool, and marveled at meticulously restored Art Nouveau swimming halls.
Liked a bath, she quickly recorded it in her notebook - along with interesting details about the building's construction and history.
More than 200 swimming pools explored architectural historian Meder in this way - and now introduces her in her recently published book "Badefreuden": folk swimming halls in Munich, historic bathing palaces in the Black Forest, "hardcore concrete buildings" in the Taunus.
In addition to Germany, Austria and Switzerland, she visited places in Italy, France, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Slovenia, Hungary, Romania, Poland - and in each case one city in Luxembourg, Serbia and Croatia.
The 46-year-old German is a true bathing culture enthusiast.
She doesn’t have much on her hat with sports, says Meder – only in the water is that different.
It’s just annoying that swimming fans have to settle down with blue tiles and chlorine stench, while joggers can breathe in the enchanting scent of spruce forests or listen to cheerful bird chanting in the park.
"One day I wondered why swimming pools should always be so ugly," says the Vienna-based medical doctor.
"So I started collecting beautiful baths."
Water surface doubles architecture
Splashes in the plunge pool and essential sauna oils - the wellness factor in baths is so great because all the senses are served, according to Meder.
And when the builders have put in effort, swimming pools can be a real eye-catcher: "In baths, instead of a floor, you have a water surface."
"It is transparent on the one hand, but reflects the beauty of the whole building on the other."
Everything visually doubles: high vaults, colorful tiles, springboards.
On 190 pages, the small-format book "Badefreuden" conveys interesting facts about the architectural and cultural history of historical wellness oases - but above all, it makes you want to jump into the blue.
The pool collector Meder discovered remarkable specimens in her research in Hungary.
In addition to magnificent spas such as the 100-year-old Széchenyi bath in Budapest, she found a nitrate-containing water in a rustic karst cave (cave bath in Miskolc-Tapolca) as well as a thermal bath, whose pools are filled with alkaline water and are located in a bottle-shaped building (V<0xC3><0xA1>rosi Term<0xC3><0xA1>lfürdö in J<0xC3><0xA1>zs).
Spectacular views, on the other hand, offer many heated outdoor pools in Switzerland and Austria: While you can watch the whole city from the Zurich rooftop pool, you can look at the snow-covered Arlberg in the outdoor pool of a bath in St. Anton - and: In the steam bath there is a window from which you can watch the hustle and bustle on the ski slopes.
Perhaps the most extraordinary pool design awaits bathers in Längenfeld: the Aquadome Ötztal looks like a Ufo just landed in the Alps.
It vaporizes from three upwardly open shells in winter, while in the background the mountains of the Ötztal rise into the sky.
Alhambra in the Black Forest
Not in every swimming pool the pool collector Meder got the smell of chlorine in the nose.
Many thermal baths smell of sulphur, while the <0xC3><0x81>rp<0xC3><0xA1>d bath in Békescsaba, Hungary, smells so strongly of heating oil that it is hard to believe that it has landed in a health bath.
The smell comes from the alkali-hydrogen carbonate-containing healing water, which is almost black and whose sluice sticks to your skin as soon as you glide into the pelvis - a wellness experience of a special kind.
In one place, however, Iris Meder was also disappointed in her search for beautiful bathing spots: when she wanted to visit the outdoor and sunbathing in the Czech Bad Luhatschowitz, she found a closed terrain.
The bathroom, designed in 1902 by architect Du<0xC5><0xA1>an Jurkovic, has now been closed.
As Meder glanced through the weathered windows of the red-white-yellow Art Nouveau building, she saw weeds swelling between the tiles.
On the other hand, the decline has been counteracted in a magical swimming pool in the Black Forest: the Palais Thermal in Bad Wildbad.
Three phases of construction have already passed this bath; you can discover not only Neo-Romanesque elements dating from the time of its construction in 1844, but also a Moorish hall in the Alhambra style, which was added around 1900.
Since the careful modernization in 1995, the Palais Thermal has been the favourite bath of pool connoisseur Iris Meder - and not only because it originated in the Black Forest.
"It is already a feat to merge such different building styles into such a great unit," says Meder.
With such a palace, the dive in the thermal pool is apparently only a minor matter.
