Deutsche Bank lets raw material business scrutinize
by Christian Teevs
Does Deutsche Bank quit its agricultural commodities business?
According to SPIEGEL-ONLINE information, Josef Ackermann has commissioned a working group to examine the consequences of speculation for the poor of the world.
In January, the chief executive wants to draw consequences.
Hamburg -
According to a study, 84 percent of Germans find it unacceptable that banks speculate with agricultural raw materials such as wheat or corn.
Two-thirds of respondents even demand that Deutsche Bank and other credit institutions withdraw from this business because it exacerbates the problems of the world’s poorest.
This is the result of a Forsa survey on behalf of the consumer organization Foodwatch.
The study is based on a report presented by Foodwatch in mid-October.
In it, the author Harald Schumann shows that the bets on the global commodity exchanges are driving up prices - and the banks therefore bear a co-debt for the global hunger problem.
The consumer protection campaign is specifically aimed at Deutsche Bank chief Josef Ackermann, even if large banks such as Goldman Sachs or Morgan Stanley act similarly.
Initially, commodity bets were intended to protect traders against price fluctuations.
But now most experts agree that the gamblers have decoupled from supply and demand – and are making profits at the expense of the poorest.
Unlike US competitors, Ackermann responded to the criticism: he promised to review the allegations and said no business was “worthy of jeopardizing Deutsche Bank’s good reputation.”
According to information from SPIEGEL ONLINE, an international working group is currently examining the allegations from the Foodwatch report.
By the end of the year, the audit is to be completed, then the results will be presented to the Management Board of Deutsche Bank - together with a recommendation on how to deal with them.
At the end of January, the head of the bank wants to tell what the consequences are.
In the end, there could be a reduction in the raw material business, or even the complete departure.
Ackermann builds on his image
Foodwatch chief Thilo Bode welcomed the news, but at the same time reaffirmed his criticism of the financial industry: "The betting on rising food prices shows particularly drastically how ruthlessly banks today harm the common good."
Ackermann is now particularly in duty as the top banking lobbyist.
“Deutsche Bank has to remove all investments from its portfolio where money is used for betting on food prices,” Bode said.
"Whether it's Mr. Ackermann's concern about people suffering from hunger or about the reputation of Deutsche Bank."
Ackermann’s insight comes as a surprise at first glance, but it is clear that the CEO wants to give a perfect picture a few months before he leaves office.
On Monday, Deutsche Bank announced that the CEO will not change to the Supervisory Board, unlike planned.
With a departure from the controversial agricultural speculation, he could improve his image.
And in order to avoid possible losses, he hardly needs to shear himself - that would eventually have to do with his successor.
One in two would cancel raw material plants
Foodwatch strives to keep the pressure on the manager high.
So far, more than 30,000 Internet users have participated in the organization’s campaign.
On Tuesday, Bode published the survey for which the Forsa Institute surveyed 1001 people on November 7 and 8.
Only 11 percent consider it legitimate that Deutsche Bank offers facilities where prices for food are wagered.
Many bank customers would also draw personal consequences when they learn that their bank is involved in such transactions: one in two would, according to the survey, terminate all investments where money flows into commodity speculation.
43 percent would advise acquaintances from such a bank, 49 percent said they were thinking about canceling their account and switching to another institution.
21st House in Vienna
The relocated pavilion
By Ingeborg Wiensowski
An architectural history with heights, depths and a happy end: The Austrian World Exhibition Pavilion of Brussels won prizes in 1958, became a museum in Vienna, stood empty and perished.
It is now reopened as an exhibition house.
If modern post-war architecture, clear shapes, glass halls, courageous swings and new building materials that are typical of the belief in technical progress, then the Austrian pavilion by architect Karl Schwanzer is a fitting and famous example for the 1958 World Exhibition in Brussels.
Schwanzer’s pavilion was awarded the Grand Prix d’Architecture for its lightweight and floating steel-glass construction.
The building is still regarded as a milestone in contemporary architecture.
He made the architect so famous that he also built Austria’s pavilion at the next World Exhibition.
With his legendary BMW four-cylinder house plus bowl-like annex in Munich, he finally became internationally famous in 1973.
His pavilion, which was planned as a temporary exhibition building, was set up in the Swiss Garden near the Vienna South Railway Station after the World Exhibition, rebuilt and in 1962 opened a museum of the 20th century - the "20er Haus" was called it.
However, the building was neither spatially nor technically suitable as a museum - no walls to hang the art, no good climate.
Nevertheless, it was used until contemporary art in Vienna got a new house.
Since 2001, the building has been empty and has come down more and more.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has rebuilt the pavilion, it is now called "21 house" and will be used in the future as a museum for contemporary art.
Tuesday evening, the Museum Belvedere, to which the house belongs, opens the first exhibition there - a bliss in every way.
Agnes Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian Gallery Belvedere in 2007, has made the new start.
Husslein-Arco, a doctorate in art history with considerable careers, among others in youth as a figure skating artist, later at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and as founding director of the Museum der Moderne Salzburg, insisted on the reconstruction with politicians and conservationists, she procured public funds and private sponsorship funds and determined the use.
Apart from contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba were to be exhibited by the foundation of the same name, a café and a bookshop were to exist, and an office building had to be built for this purpose.
Strict supervision, small budget
Krischanitz was the ideal cast for the performance.
Not only because he had sensitively rebuilt and expanded Joseph Olbrich’s Secession in Vienna and won the competition, but because he studied with Schwanzer at the Technical University of Vienna and the pavilion was an “enormously important place” for him, where he had seen the exhibitions “almost every weekend”.
He knew the original design, and he knew the problems of the building, which already lost in generosity and ease when he moved to Vienna and re-used it.
There were far greater problems with the current renovation: the building was "an energy thrower," says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade were replaced, glass fiber-reinforced insulating glass was used and the glass roof was replaced by special safety glass.
Cold bridge steel supports have been reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled ceilings have been refurbished.
Two basements brought space for new use, a lowered light trench between house and street provides exposure, a bridge leads to the entrance - almost a new building, but still the light tail pavilion.
The original exterior doors have remained, the house is painted in the old reddish-brown anti-rust shade.
And the cinema is still exactly the same as it used to be.
And all this under the strict supervision of the monument authority and with a small budget.
"Often a material had to be found that is good and cheap and also liked the Monument Protection Office," says Krischanitz and points to a rugged floor in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and conversions, the building has remained flexible and lightweight.
It had been difficult with the pavilion, "which came from Brussels", Krischanitz has recently said, a typical "drop-in-the-city story".
Such an architecture is "always in the wrong place" and still wants to "awaken a real consciousness".
In this case, however, the 21st house is not in the wrong place, because there has been an urban development happiness: Around the Swiss garden is the completely newly planned "Hauptbahnhofsquartier", with office and residential buildings.
And another lucky case will perhaps occur: The 21er Haus could get reinforcement from another Krischanitz building, because collector Francesca von Habsburg bought the Berlin Temporary Art Hall, and as you hear, she is already negotiating with the city for a neighboring location in the Swiss garden.
