The Scandal Bank of Lake Zurich
The most adventurous bank in Europe is not in Italy or France, but in Switzerland.
The UBS almost went bankrupt in the financial crisis and has since slipped from one crisis to the next.
Now let's judge a German.
That’s not what Axel Weber thought.
After his spectacular departure from the top of the Bundesbank, it was announced in July that he would take on an almost equally spectacular new job in 2013: Chairman of the Board of Directors of the Swiss large bank UBS - an unexpected and lucrative career step.
Axel Weber rejoiced publicly, praised Switzerland for its beauty and UBS for its newly gained solidity, and left friendly comments about its future colleagues.
"UBS has managed the turnaround".
"I look forward to working with Kaspar Villiger and Oswald Grübel".
But in September it became clear that everything was going to be different.
A UBS dealer in London had circumvented all of the bank’s security systems and swindled around 1.7 billion euros.
UBS CEO Oswald Grübel, a banker not only famous in Switzerland, had to leave.
Since then, the Chairman of the Board of Directors of UBS has also been regarded as a challenge - and everyone is asking: When is Axel Weber finally coming?
It has already been announced that Weber will be able to advise the bank from February 2012 onwards.
And he will take over the chairmanship of the Board of Directors as early as May - not until 2013, as the bank announced on Tuesday.
For Axel Weber, this is going to be tough.
He is not a banker, but rather an economics professor and central banker and certainly would have needed a training period.
He then takes responsibility for the strategy of a bank, which has just proven once again that it deserves the title of "Europe's largest scandal bank".
On the one hand, UBS is huge – until recently it was the largest asset manager in the world – and on the other hand has been sliding from one scandal to the next for years.
Nothing, it seems, is spared the once proud Swiss bank.
It began in the financial crisis.
Until 2007, UBS had an excellent reputation.
She combined the image of the secretive and solid Swiss asset manager with ambitious goals: she also wanted to become a very big number in investment banking.
In 2007, UBS managed $1.6 trillion more money from wealthy clients than any other bank in the world.
And, on the other hand, as an investment bank, she advanced into the league of the largest banks in the world.
That made an impression.
The former banker and later long-time bank professor in Zurich Hans Geiger tells: "I always presented UBS to my students as a pattern of a good bank."
"From today's point of view, you wonder, how could I be so wrong?"
He made a huge mistake.
In 2007, it was revealed for the first time that something went wrong at UBS.
In the middle of the year, CEO Peter Wuffli resigned surprisingly, who until then was regarded as a highly intellectual and equally ingenious banker.
A few months later, they knew why he had left.
The bank’s investment business had cheated on subprime papers and had to write off billions.
To shoulder this, UBS announced a capital increase of CHF 13 billion.
For this, she actually found investors, however, which, until recently, would have been the nose over: an intransparent Asian state fund from Singapore and an Arab state fund that was so silent that one did not even know its name.
But that was just the first blow.
In April 2008, things got worse.
The bank had to announce new billion losses, Chairman of the Board of Directors Marcel Ospel, in 2006 still the second best paid Board of Directors of Switzerland, resigned.
In October 2008, the catastrophe followed: UBS faced the collapse in view of its misinvestments in the financial crisis and had to be rescued by the state.
The National Bank bought the UBS for tens of billions of problematic securities, the Swiss Confederation gave six billion francs for a forced change bond, through which it could become co-owner of the bank.
The whole of Switzerland was shocked - because it noticed how dramatic it is for a small country when it houses such large banks.
Finally, the total balance sheet of UBS in 2007 was more than five times the size of Switzerland’s economic output (see graph).
“Once again, we could not save the UBS,” says bank researcher Geiger.
The first catastrophe was followed by the second.
A few months later, UBS surrendered in the tax dispute with America and agreed to release the data of wealthy customers who may have undermined taxes with the help of the bank.
In addition, she agreed to a payment of $780 million – as a repayment of unjustified profits from these transactions, including a penalty charge.
Thus, the UBS more or less openly confessed to having helped with tax evasion.
At the same time, she lost something that had always been her capital in competition for rich customers: the nimbus of secrecy.
After the scandal, Swiss banking secrecy was no longer the same.
This was followed by the resignation of Chief Executive Officer and Chairman of the Board of Directors.
And the exodus of customer funds.
Within a few months, the bank had lost its credibility in both key business areas: investment banking through misconduct and asset management through tax evasion.
And just as it got a little quieter again, just as it was thought, now UBS will get it back, this unfortunate dealer story follows: A single trader cheats 1.7 billion euros before the bank realizes that something is going wrong.
And it turns out: Risk management in investment banking obviously still doesn’t work.
"With the Adoboli case, one had to find that risk control has changed too little," says Martin Janssen, economist and financial professor at the Banking Institute of the University of Zurich.
The chief financial officer of a large German bank is also certain: "The problem with UBS is that it has no control over risk control."
It was precisely the idea of caution with which the Swiss bankers had long ago started to become guardians of the world’s great fortunes: no too great risks, but security for money – even beyond the Alpine Republic, if the world were to collapse.
The safes of the Swiss banks had become a symbol of unwavering reliability, such as Lindt and Sprüngli for particularly fine chocolate.
The headquarters of UBS in Zurich still fits the cliché of the dignified Swiss private bank - it is only a little bigger.
Even the location is classic.
The bank is headquartered on Züricher Bahnhofstraße, which leads directly from the main station to Lake Zurich, which is surrounded by the snow-capped peaks of the Swiss mountains.
The buildings here are magnificent, the store rentals are among the highest in Europe.
Jewels such as Tiffany's can be found here among Swiss traditional shops such as the Confiserie Sprüngli.
Swiss banks have resided here for centuries: from the National Bank to the Palace of Credit Suisse to elite private banks such as Julius Baer.
The reception hall of the UBS is accessed through a heavy rotating door.
Inside, the walls are marble-clad, in front of them are thick leather armchairs, in addition to the bank logo a large sign to the "safe".
UBS knows what the customer is looking for here: security.
This idea of the Swiss bank has supplanted both large Swiss banks, UBS and Credit Suisse, but at some point - or betrayed, as the head of a small Swiss private bank finds.
He prefers not to read his name in the newspaper, after all, like all Swiss bankers, he also does business with the two large banks.
The UBS had become much too large, he finds - especially in investment banking, where the Anglo-Saxons would also have spread.
The Swiss had nothing more to say.
"And if they do, they have long since adapted to the customs of the Anglo-Saxons."
In fact, it was the Anglo-Saxon investment banking that changed the UBS, gave it first high profits and then the debacle: no European financial institution has lost as much money in the subprime jungle as the Swiss big bank.
On October 15, 2008, the catastrophe became visible.
"On that Wednesday, the government coalition of the small seven million country decided the largest rescue operation in their nation's history," writes author Lukas Hässig in his book "The UBS Crash".
Up to CHF 68 billion, or around EUR 45 billion, was granted by the politicians to save the large bank facing bankruptcy.
How could this happen?
If you talk to Swiss bankers, they see the problem especially in the size of the UBS.
In June 1998, two of the three large Swiss banks joined forces to form a massive group.
A bank emerged that was already too big for the small Switzerland during the merger - and continued to grow.
The two different predecessor banks of UBS helped to complement each other: a rich but sleepy bank with a focus on asset management in Zurich and a poorer but already more internationalised bank.
Suddenly, the internationalized investment bankers came up with a lot of money, with which they could turn a huge wheel.
Two names are associated with this rise of UBS: Peter Wuffli, CEO of UBS from 2001 to 2007, and Marcel Ospel, then Chairman of the Board of Directors.
“I always thought Wuffli and Ospel were a dream team,” says bank researcher Hans Geiger.
"Wuffli, the high-intellectual, humble, who understands a lot about models and statistics, and Ospel, the abdominal man who has worked up from banking to the very top."
But Ospel finally relied on Wuffli.
And Wuffli probably made a decisive mistake in the end: "He thought his models were the reality," says Geiger.
“This is a tragic case.”
Tragic, maybe.
It is clear that excess came before the case.
UBS employees clearly remember the executive meetings at which CEO Wuffli repeatedly issued the same slogan: Goldman Sachs kicking off the throne.
The American Bank was the most powerful investment bank in the world.
She led the League Tables, the rankings that documented the success of the banks of that time.
The UBS wanted to go to the top.
A few steps had already been taken.
In foreign exchange and stock trading, she played at the top.
However, management consultants who were hired highlighted a weakness: In the international interest rate business, in the banker language "Fixed Income", there is a huge distance from the largest banks.
UBS has gaps in U.S. mortgage products.
To close this gap, UBS embarked on an adventure that almost cost them their existence.
Hungry for growth, both the bank itself and a hedge fund founded before it invested in American subprime investments.
It evolved into a massive machine that packaged and passed on securities on American mortgage loans – but also kept risks.
Even when other banks had long been looking to quit.
“Even in the summer of 2007, when the American real estate market was on fire, UBS bought there,” said bank expert Geiger.
So great the euphoria, so deep the case.
One manager after another had to leave when attempts to clean up turned out to be more difficult than expected.
Posts at UBS became a slingshot seat and are wobbly to this day.
Those who run the big bank now have an almost impossible job.
He must find a strategy for a bank that has lost all obvious business models.
Bank researcher Geiger already has an idea: end investment banking, focus on asset management, return to Swiss roots.
The bank does not (yet) want to go that far.
But investment banking should shrink sharply, so much is already clear.
Next Thursday, the new head of the bank, Sergio Ermotti, will present his future strategy to the world.
The 51-year-old Italo-Swiss was actually only intended as a transitional solution when the bank surprisingly separated from its predecessor Grübel.
In the meantime, he has prevailed: he is to permanently manage the business of UBS, the Zurich Bank announced on Tuesday.
Ermotti wants to drive the investment bank back to the mid-1990s.
3,500 jobs are removed.
But that won't be enough.
The UBS needs a vision.
Who is she?
What does she want to make money with?
These are the questions Axel Weber is sure to ask.
So far, he has only said that he will first look for an apartment in Zurich with his wife.
Next year.
