Smart crows are spreading in cities
In many places, sowing crows are considered "problem birds": But the highly intelligent animals can no longer be expelled from the cities, experts claim.
Some like them, others want to get rid of them very quickly: crows have been part of the cityscape for centuries, but in many municipalities local residents complain about the dirt and noise of the animals.
A remedy against the "problem birds" is not yet in sight.
Seed crows are no longer out of the cities, experts said at the first crow symposium in East Frisian Leer.
There, experts from all over the federal territory discussed possible ways out.
You are looking for alternatives in the cities
Naturalists also attributed the problems in cities to the rural escape of the specially protected crows: the chemical use in agriculture is increasingly destroying traditional habitats.
Hunting, increasing cultivation and the fall of typical breeding trees made life difficult for the birds.
Crows are protected by nature.
Large colonies with more than 600 breeding pairs exist, among others, in Westphalian Soest, in the northwest, among others in Jever, Diepholz and Achim near Bremen and in Leer.
There, in 2005, a controversial project for the mass killing of crows in the county caused negative headlines.
Critics had described the trapping of the animals in bird traps and the killing with bats as particularly brutal.
"The normal expulsion, the grumbling, does nothing," the urban and landscape planner Werner Klöver from Leer noted.
Spraying nests away with water or falling trees often has undesirable consequences, said environmental expert Manfred Kaiser from Lahr in Baden-Württemberg.
"The animals dodge, large colonies split up and spread in other places."
Exacerbation is only possible as an exception in hospitals, retirement homes or schools.
"We have to live with them, we can't get them away anymore."
Without the surrounding area, the problem in the cities could not be solved, said Mayor Wolfgang Kellner from Leer.
It is conceivable to combine the abrasions of the animals from sensitive living areas and lure offers in order to resettle them elsewhere.
"Infoboards instead of chainsaws", the psychologist and ethnologist Uta Maria Jürgens, on the other hand, promoted a completely different approach to the animals: "After all, we can best endure a pimple in the face with confidence."
Jürgens had co-founded the Ascheberger Krähen-Lehrpfad in Schleswig-Holstein, on which signs inform about the life of the highly intelligent seed crows.
The project has already been accepted by tourists.
Jürgens also had his own opinion on criticizing the noise of birds: "There is a lot of communication, they have a lot to say."
The intelligence and dexterity of the animals are legendary: Seed crows not only use tools to get a treat, but even make their own tools as a tool.
Behavioral researchers at the University of Cambridge recently tested at four crows how far the intelligence of birds reaches.
In an experiment, the birds quickly learned that they had to bring down a scaffold with stones in order to get to a moth larva.
Without a lot of training, they determined what size and shape a stone must have in order to collapse the platform.
In a second attempt, the clever crows then had to solve a more tricky problem.
In a vertically positioned cylinder, the researchers had placed a small bucket with a moth larva.
With the beak, the birds could not reach their prey.
However, the researchers had laid pieces of wire to them.
From this, all four animals formed a hook, with the help of which they then fished the bucket on the handle from the tube.
Three of the four seed crows even managed to do so right away.
