7 Lessons from the Interview with the Deceased Steve Jobs Showed in a Theatre This Week
After the death of Steve Jobs on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford, highlighting the tech genius as a great modern inventor.
But what Apple fans find perhaps most revealing in the recently rediscovered job interview, which was dusted off this week before special film screenings in the major markets, is how much this creative head understood business processes and workflows.
He was certainly a designer, a dreamer, and a self-proclaimed hippie, but he was also an meticulous organizer who diligently crafted diagrams - a man who believed that many managers suffered from "a disease of thinking," "that a really great idea makes up 90 percent of the work... [but] there's an enormous amount of craftsmanship between a great idea and a great product."
In 1995, Bob Cringely developed the TV series "Triumph of the Specialist Idiots" about the break-up of the personal computer, and he spent more than an hour with jobs in which they conducted one of the rare, detailed conversations.
By this time, 10 years had passed since jobs had been pushed out of Apple, and he had already worked hard on his new computer company NeXT, and was looking forward to the broad adoption of the Internet.
While a small part of Cringley’s interview was used in expert idiots, he says the interview’s copy templates were missing at delivery.
It was only after Jobs' death that a full VHS copy was discovered in the director's garage.
This slightly revised footage forms the basis for the 68-minute film "Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview", which comes to the Landmark Theatre this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone who is known to hate in-depth interviews, Jobs appears here surprisingly eager in explaining his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And incredibly thoughtful.
In the course of the interview, there are four times longer breaks between question and answer - 10 to 15 seconds of reflection, in which Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts and strives for accuracy.
There are also times when Jobs’ perfectionism comes to light when he seems impatiently responds to Cringely’s questions and pushes him to respond more quickly to topics or side actions of greater importance.
Recorded before the era of Pixar, iPod or iPhone, the Lost Interview seems somehow eeriely far-sighted when jobs evaluate what other companies are doing right or wrong in his opinion and represent his own vision for the future of the computer.
It’s one thing to read posthumous appreciations of career jobs, but seeing jobs here as the eager dreamer who’s on the brink of grandeur is something completely different, original and inspiring.
He has a vision of how things could and should be.
Shortly after he had done all of this, he moved on and did it.
A quick look at seven remarkable sequences of the Lost Interview:
How he learned to run a business:
"During all the years in business, I always ask, 'Why are you doing things?' And the answer you always get is, 'Oh, that's how it's done.'
No one knows why he does what he does, no one in the business really thinks deeply about things.
That's what I found out.
Jobs continues his efforts to streamline accounting at Apple.
Astounded by how costs were recorded—usually starting with “standard costs” that were calculated on the mere presumption and then adjusted with “deviation”—he developed an automated factory that ensured that business costs could be determined down to the smallest detail.
As the Pope was proclaimed:
Jobs talks about the "Blue Box" he built with Steve Wozniak, a device that could be used to sneak into the telephone company and make long-distance calls for free.
Much has been written about the device, but Jobs’ enthusiasm when he describes the Blue Box as an act of self-empowerment is contagious.
He describes how Wozniak and he would test the box by using a paid phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another, as they loop through as many satellites as possible.
"We sent things around the globe half a dozen times and when you grinned into the phone, it came out a minute later in the phone next door," Jobs says giggling.
“We were young and we learned that we can build something ourselves that can control trillions of dollars of infrastructure around the world.”
We both, we didn’t know much, but we were able to build this little thing that can control a gigantic thing, that was an incredible lesson and I don’t think there would be Apple without it.
Jobs continues to talk about a glorious prank that Wozniak and he almost pulled off when they called in the middle of the night via Blue Box in the Vatican and wanted to talk to the Pope while they were as good as they could to imitate Henry Kissinger.
Since several members of the Catholic hierarchy were called in the middle of the night to speak to the American diplomat, the two had to laugh before the pope himself came to the phone.
How he fell in love with technology (and unprepared Bill Hewlett called):
At the age of 12, when he was looking for spare parts to build a frequency counter, he searched for Bill Hewlett in the phone book and called him.
Shortly after her 20-minute phone call, Jobs got a part-time job at Hewlett-Packard for the summer.
"That had a remarkable impact on me. It was the only company I had seen at the age and it shaped my views on what a company was and how well it treated its employees."
Jobs later became one of the HP employees who visited the company’s research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw “the first desktop computer ever made.”
He was as big as a suitcase, had a small screen with a brownish tube and I fell in love with him.
I would climb up at HP as a teenager and hang on to this machine and write programs for them.
How to improve innovations:
Several times in the interview, Jobs talks about how to spontaneously invent new products.
Early in his career, when he installed some boards, he was asked by a customer to assemble the whole computer.
He worked with a payment period of only 30 days and had to think through both the assembly and the delivery of the finished equipment.
Later, at Apple, he recalls the problems he had in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember persuasive arguments... they yelled at me that it would take five years [to build a mouse that would cost $300] and I got up, went out and found a manufacturer."
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could have built for $15, which was incredibly credible.
About large companies that are declining:
Long before resurrecting Apple, Jobs predicted the ways in which so many industrial giants stumbled with their visions and lost control of their stocks.
"Let's say you work at IBM or Xerox, so make a better copier or printer, na and?"
You own the stock monopoly, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing make it more successful, so it’s those people who ultimately run the companies and the product that pushes people out of decision-making.
The product genius that has led to this monopoly position is eradicated by the people who have no concept regarding good products vs. bad products - craftsmanship necessary.
This happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
One could have been ten times bigger if Microsoft had been in the 1990s.
You've got defeat from victory.
About innovation as an art form:
"There's a lot of craftsmanship between a great idea and a great product... when you develop this great idea, it changes and grows."
You learn a lot about your subtleties.
You have to make votes, certain things you can't, but electrons, glass, robots, factories.
You have to remember 5000 things, these concepts, and bring them all together...
Ultimately, it comes down to taste, it comes down to trying to deal with the best stuff that humans have created, and then trying to bring these things together into what you do.
Picasso said that good artists copy, steal great artists.
We are always shameless in stealing great ideas.
Part of what made Macintosh great was that the people who work there were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians who happen to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If it weren’t for the computer industry, they would create fantastic things in other areas.
