Lies destroy careers and shake countries.
New York congressman and internet exhibitionist Anthony Weidner made a fool of himself when he circulated denials that were quickly refuted by irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards is accused of campaign funding violations related to the cover-up of an extramarital affair.
And then, of course, nobody who has experienced it forgets the media circus that President Bill Clinton triggered when he lied about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky during his second term in the Oval Office.
Stories about cheating at school and at college exams are widespread.
There have been incidents where teachers have specified the exam responses to their students so that they could stand up well even in their performance checks.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send a message that lies and cheating are okay.
How much deception do we experience?
Studies show that we lie between 10 and 200 times a day.
However, many of these lies are considered to be emergency lies.
Another study shows that strangers lie to each other three times during the first 10 minutes of a meeting.
Recognizing lies or “discovering lies” is one that is important for everyone to learn, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from a societal game such as Sharaden, where the goal is to call “Hab dich!”, debunking a deception is a serious field of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities that have carried out far-reaching research projects, especially in the fields of psychology and physiology.
One result of the research is that most of the old myths about lying have been exposed.
Lies look into your eyes.
They don’t always stutter, stalk, blush, and twitch.
However, it cannot be concluded from this that these liars are difficult to uncover and expose.
A trained liar can penetrate to the truth by learning something about the structure of the claim, the fine facial expressions, about questioning and timing.
I have spent several years researching the scientific results of the comprehensive and ever-growing field of debunking, and it is clear that debunking a deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and helps us to find our way around in our complex world, especially when hiring or interviewing people or negotiating or managing one’s own professional responsibilities.
Good liars are very good at assessing other people, arouse their interest and master their own emotions, and they intuitively feel how they are perceived by others.
Thanks to research, we know that extroverted people lie more often than introverted people, that men are more likely to go on "self-orientated" lies than women whose lies are more "oriented to others"—usually, they want to protect the feelings of others—that married people lie to their partners less often than unmarried people (but the lies they tell are mostly "fat."
We also know that when a person has been exposed as an offender, others feel less guilty about lying to that person.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First of all, observe the normal behavior of that person.
This is called baselining, the starting position.
It provides a reference point for evaluating changes at a later date.
Observe the posture, the laughter, the voice quality of your subject.
They should know better when someone usually constantly triples with the foot, so they don’t wrongly accuse him if he triples with the foot during a meeting.
Then pay attention to accumulations of conspicuous verbal and nonverbal behaviors.
Consider these accumulations as alarm bells that scream, not as evidence of debunking.
People who are deceiving may solidify when they try to remember their story. Maybe their feet point towards the door or they lean towards the exit, change their position in a significant way or show a "relaxation after the hiring conversation", this deep, relaxing exhalation and the change in posture when all the hard questions are over.
Askers often mistakenly signal that an interview is over, only to keep an eye out for this relaxation after the interview.
Also, pay attention to the language of your subject.
Scott Peterson's slippage is famous when he used the past form, when he claimed his murdered wife was still alive and triggered a national search for her.
Deceiving persons can also use a distancing language: "I had no sexual relationship with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or if you repeat a tricky question overall.
The most common verbal signs are subtle.
Some people use "qualifying language" when they answer a tricky question: "Well... to tell you the truth... as far as I know... to the best of my knowledge and conscience."
As a result, the answer becomes perceptive rather than factual, which often causes the alarm bells to scream.
There is no magic tool for debunking lies, but you can learn skills that enable debunking.
Thanks to these skills, anyone can rarely fall victim to fraudsters, both in private and professional life.
Controversial plan of an oil pipeline to be revised after endangered by delayed U.S. approval
A few days after the Obama administration threatened to delay the approval of a planned oil pipeline from Canada into the Gulf of Mexico, annoying the unions and at the same time reassuring environmentalists, the pipeline-building company is trying to replan the project so that it can return to normal.
TransCanada said on Monday evening that the planned pipeline will be diverted from the ecologically sensitive area of the Sandhills in Nebraska.
The company announced the decision at a press conference in the Nebraska Parliament building.
