Patti LaBelle charged with allegedly forcing a toddler to vomit out of fear
A New York family claims that the disco diva Patti LaBelle in the lobby of her Manhattan building had been given a rabies attack that so frightened her little daughter that she surrendered to fear.
The tirade of the “Lady Marmalade” singer made the 18-month-old Genevieve Monk so afraid that she suffered from “personality changes, sleep disorder” and “increased fear of strangers,” her family told the Supreme Court in Manhattan.
It was on November 10 last year when stage worker Kevin Monk, his wife Roseanna, a kindergarten teacher, and Genevieve wanted to set off for a family outing.
While Kevin Monk picked up the car, Roseanna Monk went with the luggage and Genevieve on her arm to the lobby in her building on Riverside Boulevard.
Roseanna Monk said she stopped near the door and dropped her daughter off for a moment.
"Someone appeared behind me and said, 'Do you know what your daughter is doing right now?' I said, 'Yes,' and went to take her back on her arm," she said.
LaBelle admonished the pregnant woman furiously.
"She said in an aggressive tone, 'You shouldn't drop your daughter off near the door,'" Roseanna Monk said.
"I told her, 'I don't care what you're saying or thinking.'"
She became angry and began to grumble - she used the F word and the A word and became very loud...
She had a bottle of water in her hand and began to tip water out of the bottle on me.
She said Genevieve had become hysterical.
"I said to this woman, 'See what you did to my daughter,' said the mother of the child.
LaBelle rushed to the mother who still wore Genevieve on her arm, and had to be held back by her accompaniment and pulled to a waiting car, Roseanna Monk said.
