Lower liquidity
The economics scientist Gerardo L<0xC3><0xB3>pez Cervantes, dean of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the University of Aut<0xC3><0xB3>noma (UAS), comments that the policies of public institutions indirectly explain the growing unemployment.
"What we are currently seeing is an increase in unemployment, which has to do with several factors, including liquidity losses in the market as a result of the budget cuts passed by legislation to combat money laundering in Congress, because for those who illegally pile up dollars, it is not easy to make them work for themselves, invest them or use them for anything else," he said.
Migration Stopped
L<0xC3><0xB3>pez Cervantes pointed out that the growing unemployment is also inherent in a demographic factor.
"The number of people leaving the country in search of work abroad, especially in the United States, has decreased. This is due on the one hand to the immigration problems and on the other hand because it is difficult to find work there too. These people stay here and are looking for work here, which causes unemployment to rise," he says.
Black labour
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious, taking into account the high proportion of undeclared work, which, according to INEGI, includes 60.38 per cent of the country’s employees who work without paying into the social security funds.
Unemployment and undeclared work are the low wages, the lowest in Mexico, according to the statistics of the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexico Social Security Institution) and the Secretar<0xC3><0xAD>a del Trabajo y Previsi<0xC3><0xB3>n Social (Governmental Office for Labour and Social Welfare in Mexico).
The average monthly income of the workers in Sinaloa was 5,352 pesos by September, which is much less than the general government average of 7375 pesos.
Decrease in ADI
In addition to the decline in economic activity and growing unemployment, the strongest drop in foreign direct investment (ADI) in the last ten years was recorded in 2011, with ADI of $630 to $597 from January to June, a decline of 87.74 percent compared to the $5,143,312 in the same period last year.
The Secretar<0xC3><0xAD>a de Desarrollo Econ<0xC3><0xB3>mico del Gobierno (Governmental Agency for Economic Development) for its part has a total investment of 17,280,000 pesos in 2011, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
The Debts
In the face of the economic crisis, the state government applied for a loan of 3 000 000 pesos to the National Congress in July to be invested in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities to reactivate the economy. The state congress approved an amount of 200 600 000 pesos, but no positive impact of the debt on any of the economic sectors in the country could be detected by November.
Reactions
For the representatives of entrepreneurship, the first year of government made Mario L<0xC3><0xB3>pez Valdé’s government incapacity obvious.
Miguel Loredo L<0xC3><0xB3>pez, Chairman of the C<0xC3><0xA1>mara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformaci<0xC3><0xB3>n (Mexico State Chamber of Manufacturing), said that in 2011 no efforts were made to harmonize the views of the various sectors, including the state government.
"The economic activity in Sinaloa was really very poor this year, and hard work has to be done to regain the land lost this year, and in 2012 we have to make a double effort. The efforts of all, and especially the progress of the already well-coordinated government team, have not been sufficiently coordinated," he said.
Slow economic development
Loredo L<0xC3><0xB3>pez commented that events such as the frost at the beginning of the year hampered and slowed the economic development of the country.
"The low flow of economics is the result of several events, including frost. One of the most important impacts is a slowed economy that is not moving enough to create an economic dynamic that could generate an acceptable flow of processes, products and services. Therefore, we will close the year well below our expectations," he said.
Re-defining the vocation
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, chairman of the Confederaci<0xC3><0xB3>n Patronal de la Rep<0xC3><0xBA>blica Mexicana (Mexico Business Association) in Sinaloa, declared that the state must be led to more dynamic productive activities.
"In general, we have observed that work has been done. We believe it is necessary to develop a long-term program to re-determine the economic vocation and line of the country, because it is important to activate all material and human resources of Sinaloa," he said.
There is a lot to do
The chairman of Coparmex stressed the importance of developing a future perspective that will guide the government’s efforts to a better path.
"In general, I would say that the government has achieved good results in various areas. Economic development has progressed, but it is important to develop a long-term program," he explained.
He stressed that the current state power has made progress in the government.
"There are areas where one can say that the government has acted more comprehensively, and what I can say is that work has been done and that the government is aware that there is still a lot of work ahead of it," he said.
