The court approves the 2015 transition to digital television in Mexico
The conversion of analogue to digital signals has been one of the most important changes worldwide in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) rejected the constitutional lawsuits filed by the Senate and House of Representatives against the Presidential Order, which require the transition from analogue to digital signals from 2021 to 2015, due to the lack of eight votes required to contest the law.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Supreme Court, Juan Silva Meza, felt that President Felipe Calder<0xC3><0xB3>n had not exceeded his responsibilities when he issued the Legislative Decree detailing the switch to terrestrial digital television.
With this decision, the constitutional dispute initiated by the Senate was rejected because it did not receive the required qualified majority of eight votes in order for the court to decide on constitutionality or non-constitutionality, thus the law remains in force.
In the project for the lawsuit drafted by Minister Olga S<0xC3><0xA1>nchez Cordero, it was proposed that the Legislative Decree be declared unconstitutional, since the regulations concerning radio and television are governed by the Comisi<0xC3><0xB3>n Federal de Telecomunicaciones (Cofetel) (Federal Commission for Telecommunications in Mexico), which is why the Legislative Decree would be inconsistent by the hierarchical principles.
In favor of the project, only Zald<0xC3><0xAD>var, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and S<0xC3><0xA1>nchez Cordero themselves voted.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies filed constitutional complaints against the Legislative Decree.After the adoption of the complaints, Minister S<0xC3><0xA1>nchez Cordero no longer applied the Legislative Decree and ceased all activities for the establishment of digital transmission.
The Council of Ministers also rejected the action filed by the Chamber of Deputies without taking part in the debate on the project, for which Minister S<0xC3><0xA1>nchez Cordero was also responsible.
In his contribution, the Prime Minister expressed his disapproval of the project’s arguments in the sense that the state government is not allowed to regulate by general regulations the measures that the public administration should take.
"I don't think that if you do that, it would affect the independence of the regulatory body." She also recalled that for constitutional reasons, the central government is responsible for planning strategic policy areas, such as the telecommunications sector, because it is the government that manages state affairs.
Replacing the analogue signals with digital is one of the most important changes that has taken place in recent years around the world, and it results in better utilization of the radioelectric spectrum, increased quality of the signal, and more channels.
The postponement of the transition, she said, was a postponement of the benefit of digitization, which was a decision in the public interest that not only had technical aspects, "because it encompasses economic, social, political and security aspects."
These matters, she stressed, "made the action of the entire system necessary, according to the principle of economic governance by the state, they included a group of features that put the constitution into the hands of the central government."
She recalled that many countries around the world had already carried out the digital transition through the government, even though they had highly specialized facilities.
It cannot be concluded that the government would intervene in the powers of Congress with the issue of the contested legislative decree, because the laws passed by the legislature would be complied with," she assured.
The possibility of counting the ballots individually in Michoac<0xC3><0xA1>n is considered
According to PREP, the difference between first and second place in the governor's election is almost 27 percent, with 879 votes out of a total of 6074 not yet counted.
The possibility of individual counting of the ballots is a reality this year in the elections in Michoac<0xC3><0xA1>n, because according to the data issued by the Programa de Resultados Electorales Preliminares (PREP), the difference between first and second place in the governor’s elections is almost 27 percent, with 879 votes of a total of 6074 not yet counted.
In this sense, the President of the Consejo General del Instituto Electoral de Michoac<0xC3><0xA1>n (IEM), Mar<0xC3><0xAD>a de los <0xC3><0x81>ngeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that just last November 9th, the Electoral Office adopted a series of rules to harmonise local regulations with state reforms in electoral matters.
It should be recalled that Michoac<0xC3><0xA1>n had neither adapted his political constitution nor his electoral law nor his electoral justice law to the reforms passed by Congress, so that they had not entered into force during this round of elections.
On 9 November, the Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) decided on the constitutional action filed by the local legislature and assessed the voice of the State Commissioner on the constitutional reforms as "invalid and unlawful" because he does not have the right to "determine or veto it."
Mar<0xC3><0xAD>a de los <0xC3><0x81>ngeles Llanderal explained in an interview on the possibility of individual counting of votes that, thanks to the adoption of the guidelines by the Consejo General del IEM, there would now be the possibility that the local electoral authority could partially or completely count the ballots.
Thus, under the following conditions, the votes contained in one or more electoral packages may be partially counted. The results in the minutes do not agree; the minutes of counting and calculating of votes are not available, or it is not in the possession of the chairman of the electoral committee, or there are obvious errors or amendments in the minutes.
In addition, the total counting of the fully completed ballots can take place if there is a difference between the suspected winner and the one who is in second place, which is equal to or less than one percent, provided that at the beginning of the meeting there is an explicit request from the party or coalition chairman who is the second of the aforementioned candidates.
Vote counting can also be carried out in its entirety if, after completion of the ordinary calculation, it is established that the difference between the alleged winner and the candidate in second place is equal to or less than one percent, provided that an explicit request is made by a representative of the party whose candidate has become second, in which case the electoral packages subject to partial counting would be excluded.
It is worth noting that the elections in Morelia are in the same situation where, according to PREP, the difference between first and second place is almost 0.16 percent, although the votes of 129 out of a total of 923 electoral protocols have not yet been counted.
