Formation of the new Italian government on Wednesday
The Prime Minister-designate, Mario Monti, will meet with the President of Italy tomorrow to introduce him to the new government to face the crisis that has led Italy to the brink of economic collapse.
The Prime Minister-designate, Mario Monti, will meet with the President of Italy tomorrow to introduce him to the new government to face the crisis that has led Italy to the brink of economic collapse.
A statement from the Presidential Palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, would meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm the formation of the government.
He is expected to introduce a cabinet made up of technocrats, although it is not yet clear when the new prime minister will take office.
Monti said he would present to the President the results of the talks with the political parties on government formation.
“I want to reaffirm my absolute confidence in our country’s ability to cope with these difficult times,” the former EU Commissioner said.
Monti did not explicitly confirm the formation of the government, but his comments show that the obstacles have been overcome.
The “frame is now well laid out,” he added.
Monti has managed to form a government in less than three days, which is much less time than usual. Meanwhile, Italy is fighting a political and financial crisis that has pushed the cost of debt to an unbearable level.
The new government, led by former EU Commissioner Monti, must adopt a tough austerity package demanded by Europolitics in order to regain the strained confidence in Italy.
The pressure to hasten, which weighs on Monti, was further exacerbated by the fluctuating market situation, as a result of which Italian government bonds were charged with 7% interest for 10 years, which corresponds to the state where Greece and Ireland were forced to apply for the European bailout.
Emma Marcegaglia, president of the Italian industrial association Confindustria, told the press after a meeting with Monti: "We said we would fully support this government."
We believe that this government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this emergency situation.
The chances of success of Montis were significantly increased by the support of the PDL party of Silvio Berlusconi, who had to resign on Saturday as a result of the crisis.
"We believe that the efforts of Professor Monti are destined to produce good results," said Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party.
The support of the PDL, the largest party in Italy, is essential, because so far many of its members have opposed a government made up of technocrats, which Monti is currently forming.
Support from Parliament
The new government of Monti needs strong parliamentary support to implement the likely unpopular austerity measures.
Resistance to his efforts or delaying the reforms could once again lead to a devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks is also putting pressure on Montis with its statement that a failure is a catastrophe.
Monti began his debates on Monday with political parties, trade unions and business associations, as well as with youth and women’s organisations.
