UNAM asphalt prevents potholes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the Mexican University of UNAM, developed polymer-modified asphalts to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
If attention was paid to the signs emanating from the pavement, it would not be necessary to repair almost 200,000 potholes if the rainy season in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (city area of the Valley of Mexico) breaks out, Rafael Herrera N<0xC3><0xA1>jera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at the University of UNAM, warned or assured that the number of potholes would be significantly reduced.
In his lecture "Battleholes from a technical point of view", which he held on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible develops polymer-modified asphalts to produce a mixture similar to the asphalt, but which has greater mechanical resistance both at high and at low temperatures.
Herrera N<0xC3><0xA1>jera said that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climates, such as in some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behavior of the road surface and thus avoid the appearance of potholes.
He explained that the asphalt - the heaviest part of the petroleum - is a hydrocarbon compound, one of which has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalts - and the other part a low - the so-called malthens.
Tough-elastic behavior of the asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180° C., it is very viscous at 120° C. and almost solid at 50° C., while it becomes brittle at very low temperatures.
"This means that the resistance of the asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes in one day depending on the weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," the chemical engineer said.
The FQ researcher noted that the streets of Mexico City mostly had a flexible road surface, composed of six layers of material, the last three of which included asphalt.
Between the top layers lies a wear layer of asphalt, which consists of small stones bathed in asphalt and then solidified.
Every single stone of this wear layer was bathed in asphalt.
If the vehicles move on to it and forces are generated, this layer allows a good distribution of forces in the road surface.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would spread even better," said the chemical engineer.
"Over the wear layer," he explained, "a last layer is laid out, the so-called support layer, which consists of tiny stones, i.e. sand, which was also bathed in asphalt.
Since this layer is in contact with the vehicle tires, they require a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and it must produce friction.
This road surface receives and distributes the most forces, the support layer also needs an adequate thickness and the material it consists of must be maintained.
The weather conditions, in particular humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other important factors to consider, especially the water, "because it significantly impairs the behavior of the wear layer.
When the terrain becomes moist, water penetrates into the layer and only difficult to exit, causing a softening of all layers of the road surface and consequently the appearance of potholes.
When a impact hole is created," he said, "the cover layer is first removed, while the wear layer is only impaired afterwards. But the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that would have to be maintained at the first signs by appropriate maintenance programs."
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (Mexico’s National Research System) stated that the vehicle load was another important cause of the occurrence of potholes, so the thickness of each layer of the road surface must always be relative to the vehicle load and it must be ensured that this regulation is complied with in order to avoid frequent potholes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that there was still a lot of research to be done, for example about asphalt emulsions, which are already on the market in other countries, and with which the potholes could be repaired easily and without the use of high temperatures.
