So was the work of the doctor who identified the body of Alfonso Cano
A lophoscopist from Cali went into history as the man who identified "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials plays a key role.
Last November, a lophoscopist from the prosecutor’s office (CTI) in Cali entered the man who confirmed the identity of the leader of the FARC (Fuerzas Armadas Revolucionarias de Colombia – Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia): “Alfonso Cano” by comparing fingerprints.
Of the seven lophoscopists in the department of the CTI, this week Eliazar Gonz<0xC3><0xA1>lez had been on standby, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been involved in criminal investigations for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, Gonz<0xC3><0xA1>lez worked in communities of Choc<0xC3><0xB3>, where he often had to go into the jungle for five days to reach the place where the bodies he was supposed to identify were located.
In 2000 he moved to Valle and after completing the necessary courses he specialized in lophoscopy, which is the examination of the skin, which is subject to friction, i.e. the palms and feet.
During the week of the campaign against the so-called Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was advised to pack clothes for at least three days.
Something big was waiting for him.
Friday night he flew in a helicopter from Palmira to Cauca.
He knew that he was supposed to identify two corpses, and that there was suspicion that one could be that of the man who had led the oldest guerrilla in the world, so he was supposed to take the ten-finger print of Guillermo Le<0xC3><0xB3>n S<0xC3><0xA1>enz (his actual name) with him.
However, when he reached the place where the body was located with the examiner, he could not identify it because of its physical appearance, because this did not resemble the images he had seen in the mass media in the slightest.
He had no beard, was dressed like a farmer in the area, was not wearing glasses, and was much thinner.
But fingerprints don't lie.
Armed with a magnifying glass, ink, a planting cell and a flashlight, Eliazar compared the body’s fingerprints to those on the print sheet.
He said it was “Alfonso Cano.”
That same night, this Puerto Tejada man was in charge of informing the Defense Minister, Juan Carlos Pinz<0xC3><0xB3>n, that he was actually the head of the FARC.
Searching for traces
For a dactyloscope of the Sij<0xC3><0xAD>n in Cali, the tribute given by President Juan Manuel Santos Eliazar Gonz<0xC3><0xA1>lez at a press conference on the use against "Cano" was very important.
Many people do not know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science with no error rate, which can be a key factor in resolving a crime.
Lophoscopists not only identify corpses, they also support investigations into murder and robbery and confirm the identity of the arrested persons.
When they are arrested, many offenders present false identification documents or they do not have one.
We take the fingerprints and find them in the database.
The researcher told us that in the event of a theft, he had to tear a piece of wall out of a house, because the thief had supported himself with his hand right here when he pulled out a safe full of jewelry and money.
"Walls are difficult because their surfaces are unsuitable for fingerprint removal, but in this case we were able to take the whole hand's print and identify the offender who had participated in several thefts," he recalled.
With the help of fingerprints, murder suspects can also be relieved or burdened.
Recently, a dead man was found surrounded by liquor bottles.
In the investigation, it was suspected that a family member might be suspicious, and in fact, a fingerprint on the bottle agreed.
Although this does not guarantee that it is the murderer, it is still associated with the place where the crime was committed.
A CTI dactyloscopist explained that "the fingerprints with chemical or physical reagents would be taken from the object."
When they appear, a planting cell or ribbon is used to take away.
After that, the prints are sent to Asif, the criminal database, or to the registry office.
“The problem is that there are still a lot of Colombians without IDs,” said the CTI’s expert.
He said not everything was the same as it was portrayed in the TV series SCI.
Just as not everything that shines is gold, so not everything you touch is a fingerprint.
However, it can still be used if you make a comparison.
