Energy policy:
Facts should win over dogmas
If there is a topic that cannot be dealt with on the basis of short-term considerations or because of emotions, this is certainly energy policy.
Availability and costs of electricity directly affect the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is reasonable to take an electoral meeting as an opportunity to reflect on this issue and on the position of nuclear energy.
The debate will only bear fruit if it explores the overall economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French should base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
Although there are 7 billion people on this planet, demographic evolution is propelling a doubling of electricity demand by 2050, a huge proportion of the world’s population should not have to give up a vital element.
At the same time, we must mitigate the scarcity of fossil resources in order to continue to produce electricity continuously, without forgetting the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions, an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate, in order to fight against climatic irregularities.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
Therefore, Germany remains isolated in its decision to renounce nuclear power.
This is neither the case in Belgium, which is subject to its decision to find a substituted source, nor in Switzerland, which is just intending to build only last-generation nuclear power plants.
Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name just a few, continue to pursue their projects with determination.
After Fukushima, the United States has decided to add another unit to its park by restarting the Three Mile Island plant that had been shut down after the nuclear accident.
Although the German model, which is oriented towards renewable energy sources, is occasionally set as an example, reality contradicts the discourse.
The election in Berlin will take the form of an increase in the price of electricity, an increase in energy dependence, especially on Russia, due to the increased use of import gas, and an increase in CO2 emissions caused by gas and coal-fired power plants.
The totality of these unpleasant effects will already be noticeable within a few months.
The case of Denmark gives reason to think.
On the one hand, Denmark is the European leader in wind energy, from which it draws 30% of its electricity, on the other hand, the country is one of the strongest users of coal and gas, alternately used with wind energy; as a result, its CO2 emissions and its electricity price are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the corresponding European average.
Thanks to the continuity of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill than our French households.
As the energy price in the globalised economy plays a key role in competitiveness as well as a stability pavement for industry on national soil, French companies have an advantage due to the cheapest electricity in Europe.
Any significant reduction in nuclear power would therefore result in a strong increase in the price of energy, which would make the noble statements about the re-industrialization of our country and the defence of purchasing power an illusion.
Surveys found that this was a price that the vast majority of French people are not willing to pay as much as it shows resistance to the principle of this energy source.
Let us remember that our country’s energy policy has made it possible to build an industry with 125.00 direct and 410.000 induced jobs.
Due to its strong export nature, it brings a large number of specialised small and medium-sized companies to the international markets and makes them creators of countless jobs.
If France decides to withdraw from nuclear power, a large part of these SMEs would fall victim to it, and the annual €6 billion in capital goods and nuclear energy exports would shrink more and more.
Which electrician would commission an EPR designed to function for sixty years if the decline of its producer is pre-programmed?
In order to solve the energy equation, one must admit that there is as little a miracle remedy as a devil’s work for the production of electricity.
The low-carbon solutions developed by Areva for the use of nuclear power and renewable energy bear witness to the complementarity of energy sources.
Maintaining the highest possible level of safety is an absolute imperative for nuclear power.
In France, we have a security authority that carries out uncompromising and transparent checks in existing factories, such as construction in Flamanville.
Their work teams, who have made a name for themselves due to their professionalism, are just too obsessed with the security concept.
Within 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious incidents.
Only one, namely in Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions; so it went without consequences for man and the environment.
In Chernobyl, the drama was conjured up by reactor construction and indefensible human failure.
At Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident was caused by two unprecedented natural disasters that caused the deaths of several tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will draw its lessons from this accident just as it did after the previous two.
As a result of this approach and a cooperation between the safety authorities of the French and German operators and constructors of nuclear power plants, the EPR presents a design that enables it to be resilient to such phenomena.
Since it is considered desirable among electrical engineers to build a nuclear power plant, a construction stop in Flamanville would be a fabulous gift to the competition of Areva and EDF by allowing them to take the lead in the inevitable development of nuclear power.
It is inevitable and legitimate to look for the best energy bouquet for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotions, dogmas and party maneuvers dominate a debate that equally determines our country’s economic, social and financial situation.
Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy led by Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from many angles - overloading police, court and administrative bodies due to a policy subject to numbers, compatibility of this policy with the status of a "country of human rights", as France itself had called itself.
Recently, the harassment directed against foreign students had shaped the weekly shows from the official side, the interior minister had casually announced (see Libération of 23 May) that France "did not need any talents, bricklayers or waiters from abroad".
But this policy was rarely analysed from an economic point of view.
There is a far-reaching consensus on this issue between the right and left.
From the right side, the tone was struck by Jacques Chirac, who had declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed, including over 2 million immigrant workers, should not be a problem for a country", from the left side by Michel Rocard, who had stated in 1990 that France "could not absorb all of the world's poverty".
The only difference is the degree of generosity.
The fear of the invasion of the national soil by hordes of Polish plumbers was divided from both the right and the left in 2005.
The immigrants were perceived by both camps as a burden to the economy and French society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity to which one is willing to admit to the immigrants.
Francois Hollande, in his program, is limited to banalities that indicate that partnership development allows us to solve our "migration problems".
This notion of immigration as a burden, as a problem, may have an impact on the elections; however, it is economically costly.
As economic experts Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron tell us in a recent work that summarizes the latest findings on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 p.), there is a broad consensus among the specialists on the positive impact of immigration on jobs, immigration, and immigration.
Restricting immigration would mitigate growth and harm the labour market situation.
The fears about the influence of migrants are based on the notion that they threaten to replace the local workers, especially the less qualified, by exerting pressure on their wages.
However, experience shows that immigrants are in fact much more complementary than domestic wage workers, as they mainly pursue professions in sectors that are unemployed in terms of employment.
The low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not excite local wage workers, the more qualified among immigrants work in dynamic sectors where the training is not aligned with the job offer.
Positive wage effect
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country where there is a shortage of anesthesiologists, this complementarity also between locals and migrants has a positive effect on wages and the national labour market situation.
In this way, Giovanni Peri calculated that a 1% increase in the flood of immigrants leads to a co-involved, long-term increase in real wages between 0.6% and 0.9%.
And this without taking into account the fact that the variety of ideas introduced by the immigrants is beneficial to economic growth (high proportion of native immigrants among American Nobel laureates; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants also contribute net to the social systems, in the European countries on average about 1% of the total household.
The World Labour Organization estimates, for example, that a person who immigrates to Germany at the age of 30 will make a net contribution (income minus expenditure) of around 150,000 euros to the public budget on average over his lifetime.
Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to bring about the missing intersections "with the teeth" at the beginning of his mandate.
However, these teeth, which were supposed to deter immigrants, had exactly the opposite effect.
Europe has invented democracy, now remains to think through European democracy
Democracy is a valuable good; it is also a sensitive good.
The European continent should be able to remember who, after its invention in Athens more than two thousand years ago, had suffered the whole 20th century from the tragedies of the First World War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the Gulag, but also Francos in Spain, Salazars in Portugal and the Supreme in Greece.
