"Contactless" chip cards become common good
The world’s smart card trade fair opens its doors Tuesday in Villepinte near Paris in an optimistic stance.
According to Eurosmart, 2011 should actually end with an 11% increase in global sales of microprocessor chips (EC cards, SIM card phone), with more than 6 billion units sold.
The most important segment here is the contactless technology that allows payments in public transport or payment of purchases by simply holding the card to a reader.
Compared to the 320 million sold a year earlier, 460 million contactless chip cards were to be sold worldwide this year!
Their market share was expected to increase even further in 2012 (580 million expected units) and represent over 10% of the global chip card market (6.925 million cards).
Europe is gaining ground in terms of contactless payment after long lagging behind the Asia-Pacific region.
Some 26 million Visa cards are already equipped with this functionality, and 75,000 payment terminals accept them.
In France, the beginnings are rather modest: only 400,000 contactless visa cards were distributed.
Consumer markets, however, are steaming.
Carrefour has issued 2.5 million contactless MasterCards this year.
In order to move at a higher speed, it is now necessary for the banks to equip their customers with these cards.
“Two major French financial institutions have committed to systematically handing out bank cards with contactless chips to their customers in the future,” said Gérard Nébouy, General Manager of Visa Europe France.
Banks Test Payment by Mobile Phone
However, this is only a first step on the way to the means of payment of the future: the mobile phone.
So far, a very small percentage of devices have been equipped with the NFC (Near Field Communication) technology required to carry out these transactions.
"They're in delay".
"But they should have a real upward trend at least next year."
“We expect to sell 80 to 120 million units worldwide in 2012,” said Marc Bertin, Chairman of Eurosmart.
Banks are taking initiative.
The Crédit Agricole announced yesterday the start of a test run in Caen, which will run from December to next June.
The iPhones of some 200 customers and employees will be equipped with a capsule that allows contactless payment.
BPCE operates a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And the Société Générale had also said yesterday that it would prepare for the launch of an offer that would allow its customers to pay without contact by mobile phone.
