Nord Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which runs on the seabed of the Baltic Sea and connects Western Europe directly with Russia, has been put into operation.
It will supply gas for an equivalent of 30 million households.
Russian gas giant Gazprom wanted to celebrate this event with splendor and gloria.
More than 500 invited guests, including four heads of state and government, attended the inauguration of the new Nord Stream gas pipeline, which connects Russia and Germany directly below sea level, on Tuesday on the Baltic Sea coast under orchestral sounding and at gourmet buffet.
German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon and his colleague Mark Rutte from the Netherlands have symbolically jointly turned the wheel of the valve, which transports the Russian gas to the Western European network.
With the new gas pipeline, 27.5 billion cubic meters of additional Russian gas per year will be delivered to Western Europe through a first 1,224 km pipeline connecting the Saint Petersburg region with Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
A second pipeline, which allows a total supply of 55 billion cubic meters of gas - the equivalent of the French total consumption - is to be completed by the end of 2012.
And you already let the eventuality of the construction of a third line sound on its own route.
For Gazprom, the timely and precise completion of this enormous building seems like a victory.
The project was highly controversial in Poland and the Baltic states.
The Nord Stream pipeline will enable direct gas delivery to Germany, while avoiding any traffic through third countries (Poland or Ukraine) by land.
For this reason, these two countries are losing some of their power: for them, it is now becoming more difficult to exert pressure on Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
Warsaw, most engaged in the debate, had not hesitated to compare the North Stream pipeline with a "new German-Soviet pact" in connection with the alliance between Hitler and Stalin for the purpose of the occupation of Poland in 1939.
This means that the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe has gained even greater security of supply by advocating this Russian project.
However, this is at the expense of a depletion of European energy, as the project has broken a gap between Western and Eastern Europeans.
In barely five years, Russia has managed to enforce its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich, Western countries that have strong gas consumption and whose gas reserves are declining.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us organically," Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon confirmed at the inauguration of the gas pipeline, pointing out to what extent the major gas contracts are important from the political and economic side.
All this explains the wide smile of the numerous Gazprom managers represented in Lubmin regarding the gas supply line.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an outstanding technique.
The underwater line is made of steel with concrete sheathing, which is intended to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the seabed, at about 200 m depth.
During their construction, mining fields dating from the Second World War had to be avoided.
"About hundreds of mines had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution," said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
In addition, increased measures had to be taken to protect the fauna and flora.
The line is a long line of metal, heavy like 242 Eiffel towers, which is not interrupted by anything over the entire length: neither by valves, nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project managers have refrained from doing so, as the Swedes were little eager to see a Russian state-owned company settle at the level of their coasts in a permanent manner.
"In the event of a disaster, we close the gas passage in less than a minute," Jens Müller clarified.
In the event of a leak, the gas in the gas pipeline thus escapes into the air.
However, this case is considered by the designers to be little likely, as the weld seams were estimated to have a permanence of one leak per 100,000 years.
State monitoring of the gas pipeline is ensured both by an underwater robot controlled for external observation purposes from a naval vessel and by a device circulating inside the gas pipeline.
It has the shape of a cigar, measures one meter in diameter, is introduced into the interior of the pipeline and moved by the gas pressure.
After three complete days of moving through the line at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device provides the most accurate information on possible deformations of the metal upon its arrival.
The gas pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without having to undergo even the slightest repair.
The gas circulation is easily ensured by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the access point, 100 bar at the exit point.
Five companies have united their forces to realize this project.
However, management remains in the hands of Gazprom, who holds 51% of the shares.
Furthermore, the German companies E. ON and BASF (each 15.5%), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group of companies GDF Suez (each 9%).
These five companies have formed a corporate community called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
It is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased the entire capacity of its gas transport to this company, on a renewable twenty-year contract.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, no matter how large the amount of gas that is actually transported is," Jens Müller clarified.
The financing of the gas pipeline construction was secured to 30% by shareholders and to 70% by bank loans.
The total labour costs should amount to 7.4 billion euros for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
However, the minority shareholders are prepared to recover their expenses, as Gazprom bears the liability risk alone.
The gas pipeline emerges on a sandy, pine-wooded coastline near Lubmin from the Baltic Sea.
The 4.5 meter high valves form the gas outlet gate.
Sensors measure pressure, temperature and other key figures of the incoming gas before it is forwarded to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal is supplied with one million cubic meters of Russian gas per passing hour.
At full capacity, this would be 3 million cubic meters per hour and 6 million in 2012.
Moleskine, a brand notebook.
Founded by an Italian company about fifteen years ago, Moleskine now wants to give writing a new style.
It has a flair of adventure, hours spent at candlelight with writing.
Moleskine's notebook is easily recognizable, with its black, rectangular cover, its elastic band, the egg shell-colored sides, as aged over time.
However, the Moleskine notebook as we know it today was created in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, which is based in Milan, decided to launch a distinctive design notebook at the time.
Maria Sebregondi, then specialist consultant of the company, is tasked with launching the new product on the market.
The notebook was inspired by an old-fashioned production technique called Mole Skin, which refers to a cotton coat, which is used, for example, for upholstered bench covers.
This type of notebook was in high demand among writers and travelers.
"Moleskine revived an old and almost forgotten object that was considered an icon of avant-garde artist until the 20th century," explains Maria Sebregondi, now brand manager at Modo Modo.
Success comes.
Sales increased by 26% between 2006 and 2010, with sales of 12.7 million units.
This is far from the usual production of the first years, in which only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine passes the Italian border and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to make a phantom image of the buyers, as the notebook delights business people as well as students and professionals.
Moleskine has the image of cosmopolitan, cultured and open-minded customers.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees in its early days, now employs more than 100 people and has two offices since 2008; one in Milan, the other in New York.
The company distributes its notebooks in bookstores, on internet portals such as Fnac, in small boutiques of the city centres and is committed to asserting its identity.
"We have followed the zeitgeist and its new writing needs, which exist despite the upswing of emails," said Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural trait is accompanied by the development of the company Moleskine: Recently, the brand launched an exhibition called "Detour" in which architects and artists exhibited their own notebooks.
In August, the company also launched a leopard cover on the occasion of the film festival in Locarno.
Moleskine benefited from his success and cultural zeitgeist and managed to diversify his products: bags, calendars, fillers, computer cases... The brand has the full range of articles.
In the autumn of 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, today Syntegra Capital, and opened a new chapter in the history of Moleskine.
Why does the unemployment rate of disabled workers remain at such a high level?
Approximately 19% of disabled people are looking for a job.
Today begins the "15th week of work for the disabled".
Despite a targeted public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate for disabled people is always twice as high as the average average: 19% versus 9% of the total population unemployment.
discouraging?
"No, emphasized <0xC3><0x89>ric Blanchet, Director General of the Adapt Association, which organizes the "week of work for the disabled."
"The progress made within fifteen years is considerable."
At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice, but three times as high.
"However, there is still a lot of work to be done."
However, it must be said that for disabled unemployed people, numerous obstacles persist before they get a job.
It is more common for the elderly: 37% are older than 50 years (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualifications: 80% of them do not have a high school diploma and there are only 10,000 disabled people among the 2.3 million students with a higher education degree.
In the end, long-term unemployment is also very widespread: 53% of the disabled compared to 38% on the overall average.
In short, there are so many criteria that make it difficult to get back into work, and that form the "core of the problem," says Christian Grapin, Director General of Tremplin, an association founded in 1992 that helps companies to recruit disabled workers.
So much for the factual brakes.
The unspoken remains, the attitudes that are certain, yet slowly evolving.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entrepreneurship Association for the journal La Cité stated that the managers surveyed had “a weak level of knowledge about the disabled” that was “overrepresented” by “persons in wheelchairs, mentally or intellectually disadvantaged.”
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees still have a long way to go to achieve the employment target of 6% disabled workers, as defined in a 1987 law.
These latter figures, dating from 2008, refer to a quotient of 2.6%.
“We are now at 3%,” reports Pierre Blanc, Director General of Agefiph, the organization that is tasked with collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
Evidence: The number of "paying" flats has decreased, as has the sum of deposited amounts between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
